    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-04-09T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-04-09T12:00:00-05:00" n="270"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d270">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">862t.01/40: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Observer on the Rhineland High Commission</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Noyes</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="33" xml:id="d270fn33">Via the Embassy in France as no.
                        727.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-04-09T13:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 9, 1920—1 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your April 7. In Department’s opinion action of British authorities toward Red
                    troops taking refuge in British zone is correct, Department appreciates urgent
                    need of decision in matter in view of food situation in Ruhr district and hopes
                    that negotiations may be concluded promptly with German Government for
                    repatriation, particularly of workmen, under whatever guarantees may be
                    necessary.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Colby</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
